  pages = {1029-1035},
  number = {8},
  abstract = {Motivation: Detection of single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) has
	been a major application in processing second generation sequencing
	(SGS) data. In principle, SNPs are called on single base differences
	between a reference genome and a sequence generated from SGS short
	reads of a sample genome. However, this exercise is far from trivial;
	several parameters related to sequencing quality, and/or reference
	genome properties, play essential effect on the accuracy of called
	SNPs especially at shallow coverage data. In this work, we present
	Slider II, an alignment and SNP calling approach that demonstrates
	improved algorithmic approaches enabling larger number of called
	SNPs with lower false positive rate. In addition to the regular alignment
	and SNP calling, as an optional feature, Slider II is capable of
	utilizing information about known SNPs of a target genome, as priors,
	in the alignment and SNPs calling to enhance it's capability of detecting
	these known SNPs and novel SNPs and mutations in their vicinity.Contact:
